					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">It's a violation of Apple's license to use their OS X software to run it on anything but their official products. Doing so is not necessarily illegal, though. Overriding antitrust/etc. laws might be in effect depending on where you live. (Practically speaking, though, it won't really matter either way, because this part of the EULA isn't actually enforced in any meaningful way.)<br /><br />I've run a few versions of OS X in VirtualBox, and they work well enough. Even was compiling code with XCode on one of them. Haven't tried more recent versions of the OS but there weren't really any notable problems except the usual low performance of a VM.</div>

